\date{\today}





\begin{abstract}
We study a system of a finite-size charged particle and electromagnetic field by exploiting the Hamilton's principle for classical non-conservative systems introduced recently by Galley\cite{galley} and obtain the equation of motion of the charged particle which turns out to be the same as obtained by Jackson\cite{jackson}. We show that
radiation reaction stems from the \textit{non-conservative potential} of the effective Lagrangian. We derive the Abraham-Lorentz equation using the effective non-conservative Lagrangian
for a point
charge. We establish a correspondence 
between a charge interacting with its own electromagnetic field and that of a particle interacting with infinite bath oscillators which in turn affords a way to justify the non-conservative nature of the former system.
\end{abstract}



\maketitle
\section{Introduction}
An accelerating charge radiates and therefore it loses energy. Larmour power accounts for the rate of loss of energy for a non-relativistic accelerated point charge. Loss of energy could be conceived to be caused by a damping force operating on the charge produced by the radiation field. This damping force is known as radiation reaction\cite{jackson}. \\

An accelerating charge is thus a non-conservative system which experiences radiation reaction-a non-conservative force. However, an accelerating charge together with its own field as a system conserves energy and is therefore conservative.\\
A formulation of Lagrangian and Hamiltonian dynamics of generic nonconservative system has been introduced by Galley\cite{galley}. Galley's formulation of Hamilton's principle with initial data leads to the equations of motion for nonconservative classical systems. In the present work, we obtain consistently the equation of motion of a nonconservative system (charge interacting with its own field) exploiting Lagrangian formalism\cite{galley} for non-conservative systems. The equation of motion so obtained for a rigid, spherically symmetric charge instantaneously at rest turns out to be the same as obtained by Jackson\cite{jackson}. Radiation reaction is shown to stem from the \textit{non-conservative potential} of the effective Lagrangian. The Abraham-Lorentz equation is derived using the effective non-conservative Lagrangian
for a point
charge. Finally, a correspondence 
between a charge interacting with its own electromagnetic field and that of a particle interacting with infinite bath oscillators is established which confirms the non-conservative nature of the former system.\\

In section 2, we see why ordinary way of obtaining Euler-Lagrange equations from action gives incomplete equation of motion. In section 3, we derive the correct equation of motion and show that for a rigid, spherically symmetric charge instantaneously at rest, we obtain exactly the same equation as available in Jackson's book\cite{jackson}. Section 4 deals as to how a charge particle interacting with its own electromagnetic field is a non-conservative system.
\section{Preliminary}
In this section, we shall briefly discuss the formulation of Hamilton's principle for non-conservative system and the derivation of ``non-conservative potential" $K$ due to Galley\cite{galley}.
\subsection{Hamilton's Action Principle for Non-conservative system }
Galley's formulation of Hamilton's principle with initial conditions for general (non-conservative) systems is endowed with a systematic algorithm as to how to obtain Euler-Lagrange equation for a non-conservative system. The essential ingredients required to obtain Euler-Lagrange equation for a non-conservative system are:
\begin{itemize}
\item[1.]\textit{General(generic non-conservative)} dynamical classical system and
\item[2.]generalized coordinates $q_i$ and velocities ${\dot{q}_i}$.
\end{itemize}
 Consider a general dynamical system described by a set of $n$ generalized coordinates and velocities $q_i$ and $\dot {q}_i$, $i=1,2,3,...,n$. 
