\section{A charge interacting with self-field as a system comprising a particle interacting with an infinite bath oscillators}
The non-conservative nature of radiation reaction can be inferred by comparing the system of charge interacting with self-field with that of a particle interacting with a heat bath modelled as large number of independent harmonic oscillators. In the latter case, if the number $N$ of the bath oscillators is about $20$ or larger, the Poincare recurrence time is found to be practically infinity\cite{weiss}, and the dynamics of interacting particle is thus non-conservative. The Lagrangian for a particle $M$ interacting with a large number of bath oscillators is given by
\begin{eqnarray}
L = \frac{1}{2}M\dot{q}^{2} + \sum_{j}\left(\frac{1}{2}m\dot{q}_{j}^{2} - \frac{1}{2}m\omega_{j}^{2}q_{j}^{2} + \lambda qq_{j}\right)\label{lag1}
\end{eqnarray}
The equations of motion for $q_{j}$ and $q$ are
\begin{eqnarray}
m\ddot{q}_{j} + m\omega_{j}^{2}q_{j} &=& \lambda q \nonumber\\
M\ddot{q} - \lambda\sum_{j}q_{j} &=& 0 \label{hbm}
\end{eqnarray}
The solution for $q_{j}$ is given by,
\begin{eqnarray}
q_{j} &=& q_{j}^{(h)} + \frac{\lambda}{m}\int dt' G_{ret}(\omega_{j}, t-t')q(t')\label{hbm1} 
\end{eqnarray}
where $q_{j}^{(h)}$ is the homogeneous part and is determined by the initial conditions. 
Substituting $q_{j}$ from (\ref{hbm1}) in (\ref{hbm}), we obtain the equation of motion as
\begin{eqnarray}
M\ddot{q} = \lambda\sum_{j}q_{j}^{(h)} + \dfrac{\lambda^{2}}{m}\sum_{j}\int dt' G_{ret}(\omega_{j}, t-t')q(t')
\end{eqnarray}
The Lagrangian for an accelerating point charge is:
\begin{eqnarray}
L = \frac{1}{2}m\dot{z}^{2} - e\phi(\vec{z},t) + \frac{e}{c}\dot{\vec{z}}\cdot\vec{A}(\vec{z},t) \nonumber \\ + \dfrac{1}{8\pi}\int d^3x \left[\left(\dfrac{1}{c}\dot{\vec{A}}(\vec{x},t) + \vec{\nabla}\phi(\vec{x},t)\right)^2 - (\vec{\nabla}\times\vec{A}(\vec{x},t))^2\right]
\end{eqnarray}
Lagrangian in terms of the Fourier transforms of $\phi$ and $\vec{A}$ takes the following form, 
\begin{eqnarray}
L = \frac{1}{2}m\dot{z}^{2} + \dfrac{e}{(2\pi)^{3/2}}\int d^3k\left[-\phi(\vec{k},t) + \dfrac{\dot{\vec{z}}(t)}{c}\cdot \vec{A}(\vec{k},t)\right]e^{i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{z}(t)} \nonumber \\ + \dfrac{1}{8\pi}\int d^3k \Bigg[\left(\dfrac{1}{c}\dot{\vec{A}}(\vec{k},t) + i\vec{k}\phi(\vec{k},t)\right)\left(\dfrac{1}{c}\dot{\vec{A}}(-\vec{k},t) - i\vec{k}\phi(-\vec{k},t)\right) \nonumber \\ - \big(i\vec{k}\times\vec{A}(\vec{k},t)\big)\cdot \big(-i\vec{k}\times\vec{A}(-\vec{k},t)\big)\Bigg]
\end{eqnarray}

Assuming that the volume is very large ($V\to \infty$), we can write
\begin{eqnarray}
\int d^3k \to \dfrac{8\pi^{3}}{V}\sum_{\vec{k}}.
\end{eqnarray}
The Lagrangian then reads, 
\begin{eqnarray}
L = \frac{1}{2}m\dot{z}^{2} + \dfrac{8\pi^{3}}{V}\sum_{\vec{k}}\Bigg[\dfrac{e}{(2\pi)^{3/2}}\Big(-\phi_{\vec{k}} + \dfrac{\dot{\vec{z}}}{c}\cdot\vec{A}_{\vec{k}}\Big)e^{i\vec{k}\cdot\vec{z}} \nonumber \\ + \dfrac{1}{8\pi}\Big(\Big|\frac{1}{c}\dot{\vec{A}}_{\vec{k}} + i\vec{k}\phi_{\vec{k}}\Big|^2 - \Big| i\vec{k}\times\vec{A}_{\vec{k}}\Big|^2 \Big)\Bigg] \label{lag2}
\end{eqnarray}
This Lagrangian represents a point charge interacting
with a large (infinite) number of independent field components ($\phi_{\vec{k}},\vec{A}_{\vec{k}}$) corresponding to each $\vec{k}$. The two systems defined by the Lagrangians (\ref{lag1}) and (\ref{lag2}) are thus analogous to each other as they could be conceived to possess large number of bath oscillators. The Poincare recurrence time\cite{weiss,grie} for such system turns out infinite. This affords a way to justify that an accelerating charge interacting with its own electromagnetic field is a non-conservative system. 
\section{Conclusion}
We have shown that the Hamilton's principle for non-conservative system such as a finite-size charged particle interacting with its own electromagnetic field yields the same equation of motion of the finite-size charged particle as that obtained by Jackson\cite{jackson}.
Moreover, in the limit of point charge, we obtain the Abraham-Lorentz equation.  We find that the radiation reaction is derivable from the \textit{non-conservative potential} of the effective Lagrangian.  We observe that there exists a correspondence between a charge interacting with self-field and a system comprising a particle interacting with an infinite bath oscillators which renders the Poincare recurrence time infinite and therefore justifies the fact that the former system is non-conservative.




